Stenotus gressitti

can be recognized by the mostly yellow coloration with reddish tinge, without any brown or black markings or stripes (
Figure 1
), vertex in male as long as eye diameter (
Figure 2B
), frons distinctly bulging (
Figure 2E
), clypeus one-half height of eye anteriorly (
Figure 2A
), labium reaching middle of metasternum (
Figure 2E
), ventral surface of genital capsule 1.3 times as long as dorsal surface (
Figure 4E
), hook-shaped right paramere (
Figure 4B
); left medial endosomal lobe distinctly longer than right medial lobe and with field of small spicules, right medial endosomal lobe without field of spicules (
Figure 4A
), and posterior wall of bursa copulatrix lacking dorsal lobe (
Figure 6D
). 

Stenotus witchelina

can be separated from 

S. gressitti

by body mostly yellow without reddish tinge (
Figure 1
), vertex in male shorter than eye diameter (
Figure 2C
), frons almost flat in lateral view (
Figure 2F
), ventral surface of genital capsule 1.7 times as long as dorsal surface (
Figure 4J
), right paramere not hook-shaped (
Figure 4G
), right medial endosomal lobe longer than left medial lobe and with field of small spicules, left medial endosomal lobe without spicules (
Figure 4F
), and posterior wall of bursa copulatrix with dorsal lobe (
Figure 6E
). 

Stenotus binotatus

differs from 

S. gressitti

by presence of brown or black markings or stripes (
Figure 1
), frons almost flat in lateral view (as in 
Figure 2F
), clypeus 0.8 times as long as eye height anteriorly, labium reaching abdominal segment VI, ventral surface of genital capsule 1.5 times as long as dorsal surface (
Figure 5E
), right medial endosomal lobe longer than left medial lobe (
Figure 5A
), both medial endosomal lobes bearing field of small spicules (
Figure 5A
), and posterior wall of bursa copulatrix with dorsal lobe (
Figure 6F
).

Structure and measurements.
Given in 
Table 1
. Body 3.7–4.2× as long as pronotum. Head, transverse, no space between eye and pronotum (
Figure 2B
); vertex without transverse basal carina; frons distinctly bulging in lateral view (
Figure 2E
); clypeus one-half height of eye anteriorly (
Figure 2A
); eye large, subspherical dorsally, slightly transversely elongated (
Figure 2B
), its height distinctly greater than width in lateral and anterior views (
Figure 2A, E
); eye diameter as long as vertex in dorsal view (
Figure 2B
); vertex 0.9–1.1× as wide as eye. Labium. Reaching middle of metasternum; segment I surpassing anterior margin of pronotum, reaching middle of prosternum, almost as wide as antennal segment I; segments II and III each almost as long as segment I, segment IV slightly shorter than segment I (
Figure 2E
). Antenna: length subequal to clypeus to cuneus distance; length of segment I one-half head width; segment II 4× as long as segment I, 2.4–2.6× as long as head width, and 1.7–1.9× as long as pronotal width; segment III one-half length of segment II; segment IV slightly shorter than segment III.

Pronotum: posterior margin almost twice as long as anterior margin, 1.6–2.0× as wide as long and 1.3–1.4× as long as head width; collar distinct; calli shallow, but distinctly delimited posteriorly, not fused with each other (
Figure 2B
).

Evaporatorium: triangular, posterior margin as long as anterior margin, only slightly bulging medially (
Figure 3H
).

Legs: hind femur almost twice as wide as middle femur; segment I of hind tarsus approximately twice as long as segment II and slightly longer than segment III (
Figure 3A
); parempodia shorter than claw, pulvilli present (
Figure 3C, F, G
).

Genitalia: genital capsule. Ventral surface 1.3× as long as dorsal surface (
Figure 4E
). Right paramere, hook-shaped, wide medially (
Figure 4B
). Left paramere, C-shaped, wide basally, apex strongly hooked (
Figure 4C, D
).

Endosoma: lateral lobes with dense, distinct dorsal and ventral spicules; right medial lobe without ventral spicules, left medial lobe bulging distally, covered with spicules, distinctly longer than right medial lobe (
Figure 4A
).

Genitalia: sclerotized rings of bursa copulatrix oval, not very distinct (
Figure 6A
); posterior wall faint, most strongly sclerotized apically, with wide slightly sclerotized medial projection, inter-ramal lobes present, dorsal lobe absent (
Figure 6D
).
